founder","primary_url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Allen_Butler_Talcott","primary_url_label":"Wikipedia"},"parents":{"father_id":"H03205","mother_id":"X01825","father_research_notes":"H03205 Seth Talcott Jr. (b. Nov 4, 1830, d. Apr 16, 1894). Son of H01789 Seth Talcott Sr. and U00037 Charlotte Stout Butler Talcott.","mother_research_notes":"X01825 Sarah A Allen — H03205's second wife, married July 13, 1865. Allen born Apr 8, 1867 — two years after this marriage. NOTE: Charlotte Stout Butler Talcott (U00037, b.1804) is Allen's GRANDMOTHER (wife of H01789), not his mother. Allen's middle name \"Butler\" honors her maiden name."},"number_of_marriages":1,"marriages":[{"marriage_number":1,"spouse_id":"I00179","date_year":1905,"date_month":1,"date_day":1,"location_country":"United States","end_type":"death","end_year":1908,"children_ids":["T01931"]}],"institutions":[{"institution_id":"INST074","institution_blurb":"Founding member; spent summers 1901–1908."},{"institution_id":"INST075","institution_blurb":"Studied under Dwight William Tryon."},{"institution_id":"INST076"}],"landmarks":[],"naming_inspiration":[{"person_id":"U00037","notes":"Middle name \"Butler\" honors grandmother Charlotte Stout Butler Talcott's maiden name."}],"artworks":[],"tags":["named_for_hooker","artist","painter","hooker_talcott_convergence"],"research_tags":[],"cross_connections":[{"type":"family_connection","related_id":"H03203","display_label":"His uncle founded the art fund that built the New Britain Museum.","link_text":"John B Talcott"},{"type":"family_connection","related_id":"TD0064","display_label":"First cousins — both artists in the same Hartford family.","link_text":"Alice Dudley Talcott Enders"},{"type":"family_connection","related_id":"TD0062","display_label":"His nephew Dudley Talcott became a celebrated sculptor.","link_text":"Dudley Vaill Talcott"},{"type":"family_connection","related_id":"H03207","display_label":"His uncle James Talcott built one of New York's great factoring houses.","link_text":"James Talcott"}],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"career","header":"Silver medal at the 1904 St. Louis Exposition","body":"At the 1904 Louisiana Purchase Exposition in St. Louis he received a silver medal for four landscapes: The Pasture Oaks, Oaks in Bloom, The Connecticut at Deep River, and A Wood Road. This honor — at a world's fair attended by twenty million people — came in the same year his mother Sarah Talcott died. Career peak and profound personal loss arrived together."},{"number":2,"category":"character","header":"No one his peer in painting trees","body":"Fellow Old Lyme artist Charles Vezin wrote that Talcott's knowledge of all phases of nature was unusual, and that his fellow artists conceded no one was his peer in knowing trees and how to paint them. He worked en plein air on wood panels, oil sketches admired for their sense of immediacy and rich textures."},{"number":3,"category":"historical","header":"Brought DuMond to Old Lyme Art Colony, 1901","body":"His first summer at the Florence Griswold House in 1901 was 'one of the most delightful summers that I have ever had,' he wrote, returning with 130 sketches he said could fuel years of studio work. His enthusiasm convinced Frank Vincent DuMond and his wife Helen Savier to come to Old Lyme — the biggest celebrity arrival to the colony before Childe Hassam's appearance the following year. Talcott also helped finance the cooperative studio at 27 West 67th Street in New York where Hassam, Dessar, Turcas, DuMond, and Talcott himself all worked."},{"number":4,"category":"legacy","header":"More talented than those who became famous","body":"A 1991 New York Times review of his work at the Mattatuck Museum called Talcott \"more talented than many of his contemporaries who went on to Impressionist fame.\" He died at 41 before his reputation could fully form."},{"number":5,"category":"death","header":"Died three months after his son was born","body":"On February 20, 1908, his son Agnew Allen Talcott was born in Manhattan. Allen Butler Talcott died of a heart attack at his Old Lyme summer home on June 1, 1908 — just 101 days later, aged 41."},{"number":6,"category":"career","header":"Rented Van Gogh's Arles house — 1897","body":"In 1897, Talcott lived in Arles renting the house where Vincent van Gogh had worked, alongside fellow artist Frank DuMond. He had already shown at the Paris Salons in 1893 and 1894 after three years at Académie Julian."}],"quotes":[],"sources":[{"label":"Wikipedia — Allen Butler Talcott","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Allen_Butler_Talcott"}],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"statues":[],"bio":{"first_name":"Allen","middle_name":"Butler","last_name":"Talcott","married_names":[],"display_name":"Allen Butler Talcott","photo_url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/a/aa/Self-Portrait%2C_Allen_Butler_Talcott.jpg","photo_notes":"Self-portrait. Wikimedia Commons."},"military_service":[],"slug":"allen-talcott-1867"},"I00179":{"id":"I00179","former_ids":[],"is_placeholder":false,"has_descendants_documented":false,"gender":"female","birth":{"year":1870,"month":5,"day":20,"city":"Palisades","county":"Rockland","state":"New York","country":"United States"},"baptism":{},"death":{"year":1956,"month":2,"day":4,"city":"Old Saybrook","county":"Middlesex","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM025","plot_notes":"Cedar Hill Cemetery Hartford CT. FindAGrave confirms. Buried with family."},"residence":{"city":"Old Lyme","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"classification":{"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_thomas_spouse":false,"is_talcott_spouse":false,"include_in_path_calculation":false,"descent_paths_to_thomas":0,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"is_progenitor":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"parents":{"father_name":"Dr. Cornelius Rea Agnew","father_research_notes":"Dr. Cornelius Rea